segments.text: to probably read my watch better if it were turned correctly.
First, I would like for you to explain to me how you developed your interest in oceanography.
I developed my interest in oceanography when I was a graduate student at MIT.
working across the hall one day from a lecture room where Bill Van Arks was giving a lecture.
And I overheard him in the class.
I overheard what he was talking about in the class.
And when the class was over, I went up to him and I said, what he was talking about sounded very interesting.
And did he mind if I sat in on his course?
I was too late to register, but I'd just like to sit in on it.
He said, sure, he'd be delighted to have me sit in on his course.
So I sat in on his course.
And that summer he arranged for me to come to the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution as a summer student fellow, which I did.
And I got interested in what I was doing, and I'm still here.
And here you are.
Yeah.
That was 19 years ago.
What pursuit were you following at MIT?
I was in geophysics, but I thought I was interested in terrestrial magnetism.
And I was working on a geochronology project dating the age of the Earth.
wasn't finding that as interesting as it ought to be.
The man I came to work with thought he had a serious cancer and was going to die.
Happily, he's still alive and kicking.
But I came all the way here to MIT to be his graduate student.
He thought he was dying of cancer and so handed all his students over to somebody else.
So I was kind of homeless anyway.
And I didn't find the geochronology project, that geochronology project, as interesting as I thought it should have been.
Von Arx's class sounded very interesting.
I haven't regretted it.
With whom did you work when you came here to Woods Hole?
With Bill Fennarks.
And what was your first project?
The first project was one I got involved with that summer.
I came here, and Bill Fennarks had forgotten about me.
He had organized that I should come for the summer, then he forgot about me.
And he went to sea a couple days before I arrived.
He went to sea for a month.
And he came back at the end of the month and said, oh, you, I forgot.
And I spent the next three or four years working on the data from that cruise I didn't get to go on, which was kind of dumb all around when you think about it.
But that was my thesis.
And I worked after, but I got my degree in the same field for a couple more years.
And I switched a bit.
I felt like I plumbed all I could of that for a while.
And I changed other things.
Okay.
First, what were you working on?
Oh, what was I working on?
Okay, fine.
I was working on the effect of meanders in the Gulf Stream off the coast of the Carolinas and trying to understand what their properties were and what their dynamic effect was.
And I was able to show that they had a role in transferring
They had a major role, I think, in transferring energy from the density field of the ocean into the Gulf Stream.
And I worked on that for a number of years, wrote a number of papers on it.
They're in the literature.
In the early 60s, I became more intrigued.
In fact, in the course of some of my Gulf Stream work,
I put out deep-sea moorings with instruments that recorded, and then you go back after a few months and cover the instruments.
In fact, I think I may have been the first person ever to write a paper on doing that kind of thing, at least the way we do it now.
And using the data, there were lots of papers saying what we should do and what we will do, but nobody really went out and got the data and analyzed the data.
And I think I was the first person
did do that of this kind.
And I got more interested, and I thought that it was clear that in the future there would be a big effort in doing this.
And so I devoted a number of years to trying to build up a group to put out deep sea moorings and collect data with them from independent instruments.
And that project's going right now.
It's the largest project in this institution.
It's been going for, well, I got involved in about 62.
And it's been going since then.
I was one of the people who really made it.
I got out of it four or five years ago when I got into more administrative tasks.
I still keep my hand in on it, but I don't work on it scientifically in the sense of publishing papers.
Did you ever teach here at Woods Hole?
No.
Oh, let's see.
I've got to be careful to answer that one.
Yes, I taught.
I taught at MIT.
It was a while in the late 60s before Woods Hole started its educational program, where we had an arrangement whereby people on the staff here were given appointments on the staff at MIT.
So I was given an appointment at MIT in the Department of Earth, and I was called in.
Today it's called Earth and Planetary Sciences.
Then it was called
Earth Sciences, I think.
And I was given an appointment as an assistant professor in the Earth Sciences Department.
I taught there in 1964, perhaps.
I can't remember the year now.
And then I taught again the second time in 67.
In 67, I gave classes here, but it was still an MIT course.
After that, I didn't.
That was shortly about that time Woods Hole developed its own program, and those joint appointments were abolished.
But there were four or five of us here in the staff who had joint appointments with MIT.
Did you always feel as if your career was aimed towards research rather than teaching?
Yes.

Do you think that the primary purpose of an institution like, let's say, Scripps and Woods Hole, which in this case are unique, are primarily designed for research and teaching, and is that a good thing for oceanography?
I'm not quite sure I understand your question.
Are they primarily designed for research?
They are primarily designed for research.
Yes.
Oh, OK. And do you think that's essentially a good thing for oceanography?
Do you think this is the sort of role that large institutions should have?
As opposed to?
As opposed to being both teaching and research institutions.
Oh, no.
We are a teaching and research institution here.
And teaching is an integral part.
We have 80 graduate students going for their PhD here.
This is the largest, maybe the largest collection of people going for their PhD in oceanography in the world right here.
So we can't.
We're heavily involved with teaching.
But that's a fairly late development.
It's late in terms of my own career.
I got involved about the time that our teaching program really got off the ground here.
I began to get involved with other things.
I went away for a year's sabbatical about that time.
I was involved in the early days.
I was a member of the first committee that was organized to develop the joint program we have right now with MIT.
And that was after I'd been a teacher.
Yeah, I'm not being very articulate about this, which is unfortunate.
But it seems almost as if Woods Hole itself is, in effect, a latecomer to the teaching of oceanography.
In a formal sense, that's quite true.
But remember, I got my PhD years before we had a program here, and I was a student at MIT, and the doors were open here, and I came and did my thesis.

I think if you look back at the people who first started here, you'll find people way back in the early 30s who were, say, students at Harvard or whatever, and got their theses at Harvard or wherever as a result of research work done here.
It wasn't until 10 years ago that this institution got the authority to
put its own name on a sheepskin.
And since that time, our program has grown a great deal.
And it's a good program.
All right.
And I take it then from the quality of your answers that you're excited about the idea of bringing students into ..
It's essential.
There's no question about it.
You can't.
We couldn't.
It's just a question of the maturity of this particular institution and perhaps a little bit of the field.
But no, we would be a much more sterile place if we didn't have that.
No question.
Now, as you begin to design the institution to bring in formal students here, rather than a working relationship with MIT, what was your reaction to faculty?
What was your reaction?
How did you design it?
What did you think about when you began to think about bringing in formal students?
What sort of students did you want?
What did you want them to do?
In other words, describe for me the sort of thought processes that seem to go through here.
I don't think there was much
I don't think there was much of a problem along the lines you're suggesting, because we kind of slid into it.
We had this program going already with MIT.
We had had students for years around the institution, not just from MIT, but from other labs, other universities as well.
And so when the time came to make the formal thing, and we signed an agreement with MIT, a formal education in oceanography so that all students in both institutions would be jointly registered,
We just took the status quo, and there were already up at MIT several dozen students.
They automatically became joint students if they wanted to.
There was a grandfather clause.
Any student who didn't want to become a Woods Hole student was MIT alone.
And about half the students decided they wanted to jointly, and about half decided they didn't.
But after that point, they were all admitted jointly.
We had a well-entrenched faculty.
We had a well-qualified faculty here.
We don't use the word faculty, we say staff.
We had a well-qualified staff here.
We didn't have any trouble finding people to serve on admissions committees, to serve on thesis committees.
We walked right into it.
A good number of the younger men in the institution, though not the older ones, had taught elsewhere, and so they knew what they wanted to do.
The old-timers had been here since the 30s, and they had a different outlook on things, but the younger ones, they thought teaching was a routine part of life.
We went into a fairly...
There were some pains, but they were the kind of administrative pains involved with everything.
And I think looking back at it, what we did was inevitable, and it's hard to imagine that we wouldn't have students now.
We would have a very bad problem right now if we didn't.
People would really rise up and say, we've got to get a program if we didn't have one today.
I don't think we had any problems with curriculum because we had worked that out.
We had a de facto curriculum before we had students.
We had a de facto faculty.

I mean, taking a place like this with the majority of whom wouldn't have any trouble getting a job at a university and adding students to them, you don't have any of the problems you might have in trying to create a university from scratch.
Didn't have any problems in trying to decide who was a member of the faculty or what these things were.
We still don't have much problem because we have so few students relative to the large size of the research staff here.
that the ratio is a good one.
It's in favor of the students.
There's two or three staff members for students still.
And the students get lots of attention.
And there's no teaching load problems.
Those who teach do.
Those who don't want to, there's no heat on them.
So it works out easily.
So there was not any internal problems or external problems in making a transition?
Oh no, there were internal problems.
There were strains.
There were a lot of people who said, I came to Woods Hole because it wasn't a teaching institution and I don't want to teach.
And those people, some of those people never have taught, never will, and there's no heat on them too.
A few other people who said that, when the students got here, they realized they were missing a good thing, and some of them are staunch members of the teaching thing right now.

But as I say, because we have such a large staff and such a large number of students, particularly a small number of students, particularly at the beginning, we didn't have any problem in meeting our requirements to handle the students.
In terms of placing students, have you had any problem?
No.
Every student we've ever turned out's got a job.
And I don't think all our students have the job they
It would be wrong to say all our students got the first job they wanted if they were able to write a prescription.
They might say, we all want to be a professor at Harvard, and maybe only one or two are professors at Harvard.
On the other hand, I don't think there are any.
We haven't had a problem of producing more students than we can get jobs for.
Everyone has had a job, and all of them have been pretty good jobs.
They've all been in the field one way or another.
If you were going to offer recommendations to an undergraduate student who wanted to do graduate work at Woods Hole, how would you tell him to organize his academic studies?
I would say, well, it would depend on the field he was in.
We're covering all the various disciplines of oceanography.
Here we call it biology, biological oceanography, chemical oceanography, marine geology and geophysics, physical oceanography and ocean engineering.
Each one of those.
disciplines has a different curriculum which would lead into it.
Physical oceanography is my specialty.
And physical oceanography, I would say, don't muck around with any oceanography courses in undergraduate.
Study mathematics, study physics, get a good grounding in the basics.
Come here with a good grounding in the basics, and you can do anything you want.
OK. And so I infer from that that you think that probably schools which give general undergraduate oceanography degrees
don't do the sort of work to produce the kind of graduate student who would come here for the scripts.
That's generally correct.
I don't know about scripts.
I can't speak for that.

But I know from our curriculum we've had very few people come here who've, if any, ever, I don't know, can't think of one offhand, but we may have, that have come with an undergraduate degree in oceanography.
And even the people who've taken option courses, whatever you call them, in oceanography, it hasn't done them much good because really the
Proper oceanography is a pretty rigorous field, and you need to have the basics to make much progress in it.
The best students we get are, let's say, in physical oceanography, some of the best students have been applied mathematicians of various mathematical types, physical types, chemistry types.
No ocean bias at all in terms of their undergraduate curriculum.
I feel quite strongly that that's the best way to do it.
Otherwise, you just dilute yourself in obtaining the intellectual tools you have to have.
Are your students nationally, in terms of margin?
Yes.
International.
International, in terms of margin.
Do you foresee or would you predict more international students coming into Scripps now that, for example?
You mean Woods Hall?
I'm sorry.
At Woods Hole, I was comparing you to Scripps mentally as I went through here.
Well, since I said Scripps, it's OK.

It seems to me that at Scripps that now people are talking about 250-mile research lines, international law, and so forth, that there's almost a deliberate attempt to create more international cooperation and to attract more students.
Yes, that's right.
And do you think the same thing is happening here at Woods Hole?

There will be more effort to do that, but there's also a feeling here that we won't compromise our standards on quality, and that we may try and set up some kinds of special programs, not related to, but not part of our normal degree-granting program to accommodate foreign students.
Yes, it's going to be necessary to do that.
In some cases, in countries we want to work in collaboration with, we're going to have to, as kind of a quid pro quo, accommodate their students.
And we recognize that, and the staff here is working on it.
As both an administrator and as a practicing oceanographer, do you feel uneasy about the changes in international law?
Do you feel it's going to limit your chances to do your science?
No, there's no question it's going to limit our chances to do science, and naturally I'm uneasy about it.
It's a reflection of the international situation in the world today.
The United States is one of the half countries, and we like to be able to do things our way, and there's a number of

A lot of countries out there in the world, the majority of them I think is honest, more than the majority, are determined that we shall not be the king of the cock of the walk, king of the roost, whatever.
And it's going to hurt oceanography a great deal.
It's going to limit us tremendously.
It's going to make work more expensive.
It's going to make it impossible in some cases.
It's going to make it aggravating, irritating, frustrating, whatever.
And there's no question it's going to have a very serious negative effect on our freedom to do things.
It hasn't hit us yet, but it will.
Do you foresee, then, more, let's say, cooperative projects between yourself and, let's say, Chile?
Certainly, yeah.
We have that now, and that kind of thing will work.
We have cooperative progress with Chile.
We have cooperative projects underway right now in this institution with several countries around the world.
And this will continue.
I could name 20 countries I think we're working collaboratively with.
That will just have to increase.
How do you make contact with those countries?
The most effective normal way is to work with scientists in those other countries.
If you write to the Foreign Office of Zambia, you're not even going to get an answer to your letter.

If you write to Professor so-and-so at some university in Zambia whom you happen to have met at a meeting somewhere, you may get overwhelmed by hospitality, and you'll get not only a permission, but you may even get assistance.
This has happened to us.
Some of our scientists have really done a nice job.
for example, in Indonesia or maybe Zambia, many of these countries where we've been able to do things.
Woods Hole should have a tremendous advantage with the size of your fleet in making contacts there.
Well, it's an advantage and a disadvantage.
We have a large fleet, but, of course, that multiplies the number of times we make contacts with the people, so it makes it work even harder to keep abreast of the law of the sea problems.
Why did you choose to become an administrator?
The opportunity was there, first of all, partly because I found I was skilled at it.
I became the chairman of the physical oceanography department a few years back, and that seemed to be, at the time, a natural thing to do.
And in so doing, I was able to keep on with research and administration both, because the job was not too much of a chore.
Then the opportunity came along to become the associate director of the institution.
That was more of a hard decision, but I thought I can always back off, and it may be worth a try.
I'll try it for a while and see whether I like it or not.
So I did.
And do you like it?
Not every day.
Who does?
This is maybe one of those days.
The question is, those days, yeah, there has to be some fun in them.
There is some fun.
It's nice to be able to be...
has to be able to influence things your way.
It's nice to be able to work with a lab where you respect the people and their abilities.
That's some reward.
It's nice to be able to do that.
On the other hand, there are times when those very things are things that drive you up the wall.
It depends when you catch me.
What sort of new ideas did you try to bring in as associate director?
That's a hard question, because I don't know that I'm not sure I brought in this.
I'm not sure that I have consciously been bringing in new ideas.
Maybe that's a bad thing to say, but I can't say that.

I think that one of the things I felt most strongly that was my task to try and do was trying to make the institution more open in its relationship to the staff, the faculty, and try and make it a more effective place for them to do their work.
I think with a relatively small institution, the institution is both big and small, depending on which way you're looking at it.
Compared to a university, it's small.
Compared to oceanographic labs, it's big.
But in the small sense of it, you'd like to have it as most flexibility there is for the scientists in the institution.
And you'd like to...
You can't tell them what to do, really, because they know more about what the science is than I do.
I can only be in a position, from my experience, to try and set things up so it's more easy for them to do things.
And a few times I've been successful at that, and a few times I'm sure people around here would say that I was part of the problem, not part of the solution.
It's hard.
You have to do what you think is right, and a few times I've had to be negative to people for reasons that I thought were justified.

that we've had growing pains in this institution as it's gotten bigger and it's getting more impersonal naturally and i felt one of the most important things i could do was trying to make the system more responsive to the peculiar needs of any any assigned individual involved with science you have to be able to maintain that flexibility that you had when you were small that's hard what about faculty relationships or staff relationships uh as it's as it's grown as
the number of your staff members has increased.
Clearly, the sort of exchange among them will decrease.
I think that's true of any academic institution.
The exchange per person?
Per person, yes, in terms of the total.
Yeah, OK. Is there any way you've tried to correct that?
Does it seem correctable?
Or do you think this is just sort of the nature of a modern academic institution?
I'm not sure that.
Interactions between scientists, oh, we've done some things, I've done some things to try and increase that.
I haven't made a very strong effort on it.
I'm not really sure we've got yet to the size where that's really that serious a problem.
We have a tendency, there's a kind of a tribal tendency in the institution for people to work only within their own department, and actually the department's
typically have, let's say, 25 faculty members, and that's probably small enough for them to talk to each other within as much.
The bigger problem comes between departments, and sometimes I've been helpful in getting people together between departments.
So I haven't had a conscious banner-waving crusade to try and get people to talk together more.
The institution itself has taken steps to try and get this through more kinds of committees and meetings and things to try and encourage people to talk.
When it all comes down to it, there's a limit to how much of that you can do and get your work done.
You've got to go back to your office or your lab and do your own work a fair amount of the time.
You can't spend all your time communicating.
But you've got to communicate enough so there's no misunderstandings and so people don't work across purposes.
And that's really perhaps where I sit above the department chairman.
I have a chance to see when those opportunities are there to try and keep people from doing things across purposes or when they know what things should be going on.
Ship time.
Is there any problem?
The ships are a serious problem, because it's a big part of our work here.
We've got three large ships and a submarine, and trying to decide on priorities of who gets the ship when are a problem.
Trying to fund them is a problem.
They run several million dollars a year, which it hasn't been always obvious every year that we find enough money to make the books balance.
But we haven't gone bankrupt, so we have, but it's required a lot of attention.

also hard deciding how to decide what you want to do if three people want to go and work in the Pacific and three people want to go and work in the Atlantic and you only have one uncommitted ship at that point how do you decide which group which group of people are going to make up the crews these are things that I've been involved with all right that anticipates really the questions I want to ask in two parts first part is how do you make a decision on who takes the ship or doesn't take the ship

So we've tried to do it as much as we could by trying to develop overall lines of priority and saying, okay, this year we have X ship days and we have a long-term commitment to a certain program, which means this ship has to stay in the North Atlantic.
We have another long-term commitment of some kind, which means another ship has to be in the Mediterranean.
We've got a third ship free and we've got commitments that's  we've got
desire to be in the Pacific and the Indian Ocean, let's say.

We'll try and see if we have more people want to go to one than the other, so the one with the least number of people can be put off another year and try and build up a little more strength, as an example.
These are all kind of common sense things.
And then we have a head-to-head conflict.
We'd have to resolve it by trying to look at it from an institution point of view and based on its scientific merit.
And that's difficult because you can't say biology is better than physical oceanography necessarily.
But you do it.
Usually there's some other factors that you throw into the balance that make the difference.

And we usually, final decisions like this are decided in this institution by what we call staff council of the various department chairmen and the directors getting together and deciding, okay, we've got a head-to-head problem here.
We only have one ship and two people who want it, and therefore it'll go to so-and-so.
Our SIP schedules are made typically 18 months ahead of time, so there's usually a lot of time for
If we make a bad decision, there's a lot of time for people to protest and get things straightened out.
And until the day the ship sails, usually we're never exactly sure of the ship's schedule.
But you can see on the wall there our schedules for 77, 78.
We'll start in right now on 79.
And then, oh, in a couple of months, I'll sound a memo to people saying, we'd like to have a written input from you on what your major is.
requirements are for ships in 1979.

We'll only have one great big bash of a meeting in a meeting room, and everybody will stand up and say, well, I want to use that ship for eight weeks here, and somebody else says, I want to use it for 12 weeks here, and so forth.
We'll put them all together.
If it solves, if we put them all end to end, and we've got four ships or whatever, and they all solve, fine.
Our experience has been we usually got one and a half times as many requests as we have ship days.
Then we have a problem.
We know from experience that we don't get enough money from the funding agencies in Washington to support one and a half times as many ship days.
We know the problem is going to be self-regulating.
The question is where is that we're likely... Can we anticipate which programs would like to fall out because they're not yet well enough to find, which is usually the case, why things fall out.
Not because they're bad, but people haven't got their ducks in order yet and their program doesn't quite work.
And...
We cast out the programs we think are weak if we can identify them.
By hook or by crook, we usually get it down.
It's not a process which can...

It's not a linear process, the one that we can say, well, here's a formula for how we do it, because it interacts with the scientists, groups of scientists, with the funding agencies, and with our hardware, with the ships themselves.
We don't want to send... Because of the crew morale, we've got a ship right now which is in the...
Let's see.
We just got one.
I'm sorry.
We got one back just a few months ago from the Indian Ocean.
It had been away 22 months.
We're not going to send it again on another 22-month cruise for quite a while.
It's not fair to the crew members.
So that ship is ruled out for going on the next large cruise.
Our next large cruise is going to be in 1978 when we send that ship into the Pacific.
It'll be off a different ship than we sent to the Indian Ocean simply because of the morale of the crew.
We just can't do that to them.
We've got all kinds of constraints.
There's so many constraints that go on and on.
I'm not sure it's very interesting.
Just use common sense to solve it.
You have to go through one by one all these problems.
Do you feel that all your students should go to C?
I think our students mostly all do go to C. It depends on the student.
We have a few students who are working on problems which involves a computer, for example, doing numerical modeling or something.
They can do perfectly well if they never go to sea, although even in those cases, we generally encourage them to go to sea.
I don't think we've turned out students recently who haven't been at least once to see what it's like.
Some people go to sea, and they just go for months and months, and they're chief scientists and run things and everything else.
That's the other extreme.
I don't know why you picked on students.
Why didn't you say, should our staff go to sea?
Because I was thinking in terms of the planning program.
I assume most of your staff at one time or another has been to sea.
Oh, no.
We've got staff here who have never been to sea in their life.
They've been here their whole career here.
And the day they retire, they'll never have been to sea.
Stonewall was telling me that he wished he had gone to sea more, but his work had never really let him do so.
Yeah.
Yeah.
He doesn't.
Well, he goes to sea a fair amount compared with some.
There are people in this lab who have never been to sea in their life, and they're good, productive oceanographers.
Good.

They're working in a laboratory studying specimens somebody else brings back, or they're working in an office with a computer and a slide rule doing theoretical studies or something like that, or studying something that doesn't require them to go to sea.
For some, doing modeling, they don't have to go to sea.
They haven't.
And there are few, but there are some.
I think the students are the same as everybody else.
There's a cross-section of them.
Although you might argue that part of the educational process would be at least one trip to sea to find out what they're talking about.
There's been some complaint among older oceanographers that younger oceanographers don't go to sea often enough, don't get their feet wet, is usually what they say.
Yeah, I heard it.
I agree that they say that.
It's the old Iron Man, Wooden Chip Syndrome.
Oceanography's going through a hero phase back in the early days, and the old-timers still feel it.
I'm not sure it's necessary to be a hero to be a good scientist.
